      <Devices>
        <NotePadDevice type="NotePadDevice">
          <SelectedPresetName>Init</SelectedPresetName>
          <SelectedPresetLibrary>Bundled Content</SelectedPresetLibrary>
          <SelectedPresetIsModified>true</SelectedPresetIsModified>
          <IsMaximized>true</IsMaximized>
          <IsSelected>false</IsSelected>
          <IsActive>
            <Value>0.0</Value>
            <Visualization>Device only</Visualization>
          </IsActive>
          <Paragraphs>
            <Paragraph>Glitchbox is a multi-effect unit for degrading sound input signals that incorporates nested doofers (Filter Chaos, Lofi Chaos, Xmod Chaos, &amp; Repeater Chaos) to achieve complex glitching behavior. </Paragraph>
            <Paragraph>A limiter is enabled by default at the end of the signal chain to protect ears and speakers. “OFF&lt;&gt;ON” should be self evident, but each time this macro engages with the “ON” state, it calls new random values from the sub units, creating new glitches. Try automating this parameter :) “Switchrate” determines the overall rate of random change among all enabled sub units. “Glitch rate” affects the Divisor values of the Repeater Chaos sub unit. Higher values skew towards faster repeats. The next three macros determine whether the respective sub units are enabled or not. TIP: try creating different orderings of subunits within the doofer for different flavors of effect. “Degrader” controls Lofi sample rate, and “&lt;filterQ&gt;” controls just that.</Paragraph>
          </Paragraphs>
        </NotePadDevice>
